      "title": "Demonstrating the reliability of the difference score in the measurement of change",
      "abstract": "The reliability of the difference score (a.k.a., gain score) has been one of the most discussed, yet least understood, topics in the measurement of change. Demonstrations of the lack of reliability of the difference score are prevalent. Most discussions of the reliability of the difference score in the measurement of change literature have recited and served to document the assertions by Lord that \"differences between scores tend to be much more unreliable than the scores themselves\" (1956, p. 429) and that \"the difference between two fallible measures is frequently much more fallible than either\" (1963, p. 32). Rogosa, Brandt, and Zimowski (1982) explained that these assertions are accurate only in extreme, yet frequently examined, situations.' The reliability of a measure represents the ability of that measure to distinguish among individuals on a particular trait or true score. Hence, when all individuals display nearly the same true change, naturally the difference score is unable to adequately distinguish the true change among the individuals. Consequently, the reliability of the difference score will be very low. As most previous investigations have emphasized situations for which true change varies little across individuals, it is not surprising that criticisms of the difference score, because of its low reliability, dominate the literature on change. On the other hand, when individual differences in true change do exist, the difference score does a good job in distinguishing among individuals (see Rogosa et al., 1982). The purpose of this paper is to demonstrate explicitly that the difference score is reliable in many important situations. We consider measurements on each of n persons at time 1 and at time 2; the observed score for person j (j = 1,... n) is Xij at time 1 and X2j at time 2. We assume a classical test theory model for the observed scores: X,j = l,j + E,j and X2j = t2j + e2j where l,j and ~2j are the true scores for person j at times 1 and 2, respectively, and e,j and E2j are the measurement errors at times 1 and 2. True change for person j is written: Aj = ~2j lj. The difference (gain) score for person j, which estimates the true change, is written: Dj = X2j Xj. The reliabilities of X, and X2 are denoted by p(X,) and p(X2). The reliability of the difference score is denoted by p(D)."
